It's not a bug.  It's Elasticsearch telling you that you can't name the index the same as one already in existence.  Elasticsearch gives you the exact same error if you do this manually.  I'll show you what happens using console, as follows.

I'll create this one, like what you have: 
```
PUT %3Ctest-%7Bnow%2FH%7BYYYY.MM.dd.HH%7D%7D-1%3E
{
  "settings": {
    "index": {
      "number_of_shards": 1,
      "number_of_replicas": 0
    }
  },
  "aliases": {
    "test": {}
  }
}
```
_(You have to use URL-encoding for those characters in Console. It's exactly the same sequence you provided:_ `<test-{now/H{YYYY.MM.dd.HH}}-1>`_)_

Here's the result:
```
{
  "acknowledged": true,
  "shards_acknowledged": true,
  "index": "test-2018.05.19.21-1"
}
```
Now, if I send a rollover request, with that same name _in the same hour:_
```
POST /test/_rollover/%3Ctest-%7Bnow%2FH%7BYYYY.MM.dd.HH%7D%7D-1%3E
{
  "conditions": {
    "max_age":   "1s"
  }
}
```
This is the result (which is what you're getting in Curator):
```
{
  "error": {
    "root_cause": [
      {
        "type": "resource_already_exists_exception",
        "reason": "index [test-2018.05.19.21-1/qdStmzQsRqCwJOj1VSZgJQ] already exists",
        "index_uuid": "qdStmzQsRqCwJOj1VSZgJQ",
        "index": "test-2018.05.19.21-1"
      }
    ],
    "type": "resource_already_exists_exception",
    "reason": "index [test-2018.05.19.21-1/qdStmzQsRqCwJOj1VSZgJQ] already exists",
    "index_uuid": "qdStmzQsRqCwJOj1VSZgJQ",
    "index": "test-2018.05.19.21-1"
  },
  "status": 400
}
```

You see the same `400` error with the accompanying `resource_already_exists_exception` in your Curator log.  Because you're doing a named-by-hour rollover, and since the hour hasn't rolled over, ending with `-1` means a collision, as the number cannot increase.  

## Proposed Solution
I think what you want is to do is describe the name pattern just once.

If I change the index creation pattern to be per minute (I'm not going to wait an hour to demonstrate this):

```
%3Ctest-%7Bnow%2Fm%7BYYYY.MM.dd.HH.mm%7D%7D-1%3E
(which is <test-{now/m{YYYY.MM.dd.HH.mm}}-1>)
```
I get an index named: `test-2018.05.19.22.02-1`

When I rollover _within the same minute_ and do **not specify a new index name**, I will see this output:
```
{
  "old_index": "test-2018.05.19.22.02-1",
  "new_index": "test-2018.05.19.22.02-000002",
  "rolled_over": true,
  "dry_run": false,
  "acknowledged": true,
  "shards_acknowledged": true,
  "conditions": {
    "[max_age: 1s]": true
  }
}
```
Please note that you cannot prevent Elasticsearch from the zero-padding of the trailing number with this approach.  [This is documented](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/6.2/indices-rollover-index.html#_naming_the_new_index):
> If the name of the existing index ends with `-` and a number — e.g. `logs-000001` — then the name of the new index will follow the same pattern, incrementing the number (`logs-000002`). The number is zero-padded with a length of 6, regardless of the old index name.

Subsequently, if I rollover in a new minute, and **do not specify a new index name**, I will see this output:
```
{
  "old_index": "test-2018.05.19.22.02-000002",
  "new_index": "test-2018.05.19.22.04-000003",
  "rolled_over": true,
  "dry_run": false,
  "acknowledged": true,
  "shards_acknowledged": true,
  "conditions": {
    "[max_age: 1s]": true
  }
}
```
Elasticsearch automatically preserves the naming pattern (`test-2018.05.19.22.02` moves to `test-2018.05.19.22.04`) and just appends digits to the end.  No more naming magic required from you, which is needed if you will have more than 1 index per date period you have in your index date-math name.

In my mind, it's so much simpler to just have numbered rollovers, e.g. `test-000001` and let Curator do the date math with the `period` and/or `age` filters using the [`field_stats`](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/client/curator/current/filtertype_age.html#_literal_field_stats_literal_based_ages) calculated ages.  Then it just doesn't matter when it rolls over.  Even at 2 rollovers per hour, my rough calculation would be 5.7 years worth of digits in a 1 to 99999 count.

