Here's an alternative that is a little bit simpler (though the _cleanup capsule will be visible to Python code):

```C++
static int unused; // the capsule needs something to reference
py::capsule cleanup(&unused, [](PyObject *) { std::cout << "Cleanup!" << std::endl; });
m.add_object("_cleanup", cleanup);
```

The behavior here is essentially the same as in C++:
```c++

struct Base {
    void foo() { }
    void foo(int) { }
};

struct Derived : Base {
    void foo() { }
};

int main() {
    auto d = Derived();
    d.foo(1);
    // ^^^^^ compiler error
    // too many arguments to function call, expected 0, have 1;
    // did you mean 'Base::foo'?
}
```

Adding a function to the derived class shadows the entire overload set in the base class (not just the function with the same signature). The solution in C++ is to add `using Base::foo;` to `Derived`. pybind11 doesn't have an equivalent for `using`, but the same effect can be achieved by binding the same functions again in the derived class.

@garth-wells In your case, this would just be a case of adding `.def("__imul__", (VectorBase& (VectorBase::*)(float)) &VectorBase::operator*=)` to the `Vector2` bindings.

